    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-05-24T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-05-24T17:00:00-05:00" n="402"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d402">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">716.5 MSP/5–2454:Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in El Salvador</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_MMJ1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">McDermott</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                        <lb/>
                        <gloss target="#t_niact1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">niact</hi>
                        </gloss>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">San Salvador</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-05-24T16:00:00-06:00"
                            >May 24, 1954—4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>119. Pouched Guatemala City and Tegucigalpa. During conversation this morning
                    President twice emphasized extreme urgency receipt certain arms and more
                    particularly munitions even before final signature of military assistance
                    agreements. Said he had been informed US planes were today landing at
                    Tegucigalpa with certain arms for Honduran Government. He said in view recent
                    developments, and particularly reports that certain arms from <gloss
                        target="#t_SS1">SS</gloss>
                    <hi rend="italic">Alfhem</hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d402fn1">Reference is to the vessel which arrived at Puerto
                        Barrios, Guatemala, on May 15, 1954, containing arms shipments of
                        Czechoslovakian origin. For additional documentation on this subject, see
                            <ref target="#pg_1111">pp. 1111</ref> ff.</note> had been unloaded at
                    Chiquimula, he was ordering partial but secret mobilization. Added there were
                    reports truck movement Chiquimula region and that despite possible consequences,
                    Honduran planes would today make reconnaissance that area.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_OO1">Osorio</persName> said would have Chief General
                        Staff<note n="2" xml:id="d402fn2">Col. <persName>Alberto
                            Escamilla</persName>.</note> make available to Army Attaché tomorrow
                    minimum list most indispensable arms and munitions. At this point again
                    emphasized urgency of need and said government would pay since it must have
                    munitions although possibly its arms almost sufficient for emergency.</p>
                <p>I do not know how they might be supplied but urge Department explore every
                    possibility. I advance suggestion arms, munitions might be furnished Army
                    Mission as training aids.</p>
                <p>Please inform.<note n="3" xml:id="d402fn3">
                        <p>Telegram 121, to San Salvador, dated May 25, 1954, signed by Assistant
                            Secretary <persName corresp="#p_HHF1">Holland</persName>, stated that
                            grant military assistance could be furnished expeditiously to El
                            Salvador, provided that the Salvadoran Government approved the General
                            Military Plan for the Defense of the American Continent, signed and
                            ratified a military assistance agreement with the United States, and
                            approved a related bilateral military plan prepared by the Department of
                            Defense (716.5 MSP/5–2454).</p>
                        <p>The General Military Plan was approved by the Inter-American Defense
                            Board on Nov. 15, 1951, and by the United States on Mar. 20, 1952; for
                            pertinent information, see the editorial note, <ref
                                target="frus1951v02#pg_1028">
                                <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1951, vol. <hi
                                    rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p. 1028</ref>.</p>
                    </note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MMJ1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">McDermott</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
